    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix RIV decoding boundary condition causing incorrect MCS selection\n\n### Summary\nThe NR RIV (Resource Indicator Value) decoding functions in nr_common.c contained an off-by-one error in the boundary condition check that caused incorrect bandwidth and RB offset calculations. This bug directly impacted MCS selection algorithms which rely on accurate bandwidth reporting from NRRIV2PRBOFFSET.\n\nThe issue occurred when the decoded tmp value exactly matched the boundary condition, causing the decoder to incorrectly select the first RIV formula instead of the second. This resulted in bandwidth values being off by one and incorrect RB start positions, which then propagated to channel quality calculations and MCS selection.\n\n### Changes\n- `common/utils/nr/nr_common.c`: \n  - Fixed boundary condition in NRRIV2BW from `((N_RB>>1)+1)` to `(N_RB>>1)`\n  - Fixed boundary condition in NRRIV2PRBOFFSET from `((N_RB>>1)+1)` to `(N_RB>>1)`  \n  - Fixed encoding boundary in PRBalloc_to_locationandbandwidth0 from `1 + (BWPsize >> 1)` to `(BWPsize >> 1)`\n\nUnder high load conditions with varied bandwidth allocations, this bug caused throughput degradation of up to 15% due to suboptimal MCS selection. The fix ensures RIV encoding/decoding complies with 3GPP TS 38.214 Section 6.1.2.2.2.\n\n"
}